04563nam a22006135i 9780520929142DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209291427 a10.1525/97805209291422doi  a(DE-B1597)648162  a(OCoLC)1408681651  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDK687.M59 2003ebaDK687.M59 2003 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a947.56/081 aMiller/Miller, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArmenia :bPortraits of Survival and Hope /cMiller/Miller; ed. by Lorna Touryan Miller, Donald E. Miller, Jerry Berndt. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b76 b/w photographs, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Massive Destruction -- t2. Random Violence -- t3. Fighting for Survival -- t4. Surviving the Winter -- t5. “We Live with Hope” -- t6. Concluding Reflections -- tEpilogue: Ten Years after Independence -- tAppendix 1: Research Methodology -- tAppendix 2: Interview Guide -- tAppendix 3: Interviewees -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA remarkable view of how geopolitics affects ordinary people, this book documents, in words and pictures, the lives of Armenians in the last two decades. Based on intimate interviews with three hundred Armenians and featuring Jerry Berndt's superb photographs, it brings together firsthand testimony about the social, economic, and spiritual circumstances of Armenians during the 1980s and 1990s, when the country faced an earthquake, pogroms, and war. At times shocking and deeply emotional, Armenia: Portraits of Survival and Hope is a story of extreme suffering and hardship, a searching look at the fight for independence, and an exceptionally complex portrait of the human spirit. A companion to the Millers' highly acclaimed work Survivors: An Oral History of the Armenian Genocide, which documented the genocide of 1915, this book focuses on four groups of people: survivors of the earthquakes that devastated northwestern Armenia in 1988; refugees from Azerbaijan who fled Baku and Sumgait because of pogroms against them; women, children, and soldiers who were affected by the war in Nagorno-Karabakh; and ordinary citizens who survived several winters without heat because of the blockade against Armenia by Turkey and Azerbaijan. The Millers' narrative situates these accounts contextually and thematically, but the voices of individuals remain paramount. The Millers also describe their personal experiences in repeated research trips, inviting us to look beyond the headlines and think beyond the circumstances of our own lives as they bring contemporary Armenia to life.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArmenianszAzerbaijan. 0aNagorno-Karabakh Conflict, 1988-1994. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 4aMiddle East. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aBerndt, Jerry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiller, Donald E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTouryan Miller, Lorna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023492540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092914240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929142423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520929142/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles